CaseSummary.Summary: Vehicle one (V1 - case vehicle). a 2000 Chevrolet Malibu, 4-door sedan was traveling north in the right northbound lane of a limited access, four-lane, divided freeway (two lanes northbound, open median, two lanes southbound). Vehicle two (V2), a 1998 International tractor-trailer was traveling north in the left northbound lane of the same roadway but was slightly behind V1. For an unknown reason, the driver of V1 suddenly veered to the left and into the left northbound lane. The driver of V2 could not avoid V1 and the front of V2 struck the left-side of V1. The 63-year-old male driver of V1 (case occupant) was not using the available 3-point seat belt and no airbags deployed. This vehicle is equipped with frontal-impact airbags that did not deploy, but is not equipped with side-impact airbags. The driver of V1 was transported to a regional level-one trauma center via helicopter. Both vehicles were reportedly towed due to disabling damage. The driver of V1 expired 3 months post-crash due to a pre-exisiting illness not attributed to the crash.

CirenCaseForm.InjuryAnalysis:
The case occupant is the 178 cm (5' 10"), 70 kg (154 lb), 63-year-old male driver of a 2000 Chevrolet Malibu, 4-door sedan that veered quickly to the left while traveling in the right lane of a limited access freeway. His vehicle was subsequently struck in the left side by the front of a 1998 International, tractor-trailer unit. The impact was classified as severe. The WinSmash reconstruction program calculated an equivalent barrier speed of 63 kmph (38 mph), which appeared to be consistent with the observed damage. The case occupant was not using the available 3-point seat belt. The frontal-impact airbags did not deploy. This vehicle was not equipped with side-impact airbags.
In response to the 9 o'clock direction of force, the driver moved to the left, relative to the vehicle interior. He sustained fractures to the left superior and inferior pubic rami and the right pubic symphysis due to contact with the left interior door armrest. He sustained a laceration to the left parietal scalp due to contact with the D-ring of the drivers seatbelt system. He also sustained fractures to the right 1-3 and 6th ribs probably due to rebound contact with the side of the right-front seat backrest. It should be noted that due to ongoing medical care for a pre-existing condition, these ribs, in particular, were not in the best condition. He also sustained a burst fracture to the T7 vertebra from an unknown source. This patient expired 3-months post-crash from his pre-existing medical condition.
